<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Communities &amp; Local Government Committee inquiry on the implementation of welfare reform by local authorities</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Borough of Hackney</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hackney is a densely populated inner </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> borough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is one of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">capital's most vibrant cultural and creative places. It is a young borough home to people from many different backgrounds. It has the second highest number of people living in poverty in the country although no areas are particularly poor or wealthy.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Council recognises the need for reform of welfare provision, and recognises that the key route out of poverty is employment. Therefore we support the principles of simplification and of making work pay. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, for the reforms to be most effective they</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">grow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">safeguarding of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> affordable housing provision and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assist in attracting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> investment into the local economy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Council </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is concerned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with the impact of the welfare reforms on the ability to live in Hackney.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has made a significant commitment to assisting workless households into employment, particularly at entry level jobs for young people and those with limited skills and experience. However, this activity is undermined </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">whe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rents are unaffordable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> households</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The household is effectively better off being unemployed elsewhere than in work in Hackney. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Affordability of housing is a key driver in the economic wellbeing of an area, affecting how attractive it is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">potential new business. In particul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ar, small and medium enterprises rely on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the availability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a local workforce able to take low paid employment.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The welfare reforms will lead to greater mobility </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undermining</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> social cohesion, particularly for vulnerable and isolated households, or where g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ang related activity is involved. Linked to this are concerns that systems are not flexible enough to redirect resources to more affordable areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as demand increases.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hackney Council calls on the Government to reconsider those aspects of the reform progra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mme that are inhibiting the opportunity of the community to live and work in the borough:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">By recognising the significantly higher housing costs in London and setting a London Benefit Cap accordingly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or by removing support for housing costs from the cap cal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">culation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Allow councils to set a ceiling on Affordable Rents to ensure they do not exceed cap levels</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Allow additional protection from the cap for those households actively engaged in training/work programme activity, particularly where access to a scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is not available or it is unreasonable to expect the applicant to accept a placement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Re-establishing the link between uprating of financial support for housing costs and the local market rent levels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 68.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Allow housing support payments paid direct to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">landlord should remain for Registered Providers and Council tenants, and for Private landlords who engage with Private Sector Leasing schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.   </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">orough of Hackney</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is one of the most diverse communities in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">population in excess of 246,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> half </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of whom are from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">BME communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">speaking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 118 community languages</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It is also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">among</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the most deprived</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with 19.3% of the population receiving key out of work benefits</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hackney has over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">44,000 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">households receiving housing support. Most of these households </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are seeing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the level of support they receive reduced as a consequence of the reforms.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The benefits cap alone </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is due to impact on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">789</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> households in Hackney</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, who will have their housing support c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ut by an average of £99.00.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As at the end of April 2013, it was estimated that Hackney had 4,255 households under-occupying their homes and affected by the removal of the spare room subsidy, with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">amount </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of support paid to these households reduced by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a total of £</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4.6 million. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As for the private sector, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there are approximately 9,000 recipients of Local Housing Allowance in Hackney, with around 5,000 of these households </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">having the amount of support cut</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by the restrictions in the Local Housing Allowance r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">mpact of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">reform of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> housing support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Hackney</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> residents</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hackney Council has been monitoring the impact of the reform programme on the local community. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is evidence that l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iving circumstances for LHA recipients have deteriorated since </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the introduction of the LHA restrictions/caps. The lack of suitable, accessible supply has meant that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">▪</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">large average weekly shortfalls are occurring on new LHA claims from April 2012, notably on shared accommodation (£51pw), one beds (£32pw) and 3 beds (£3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4pw)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">▪</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">well over 30% of new claims for 2 bed+ lettings between June and November 2012 had insufficient bedrooms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">▪</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Based on a 2010 baseline, there has been a 36% increase in the level of threatened and/or actual illegal eviction reported to Hackney Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">▪</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">amongst those on low incomes not eligible for LHA, officers are seeing evidence of increased use of sub-standard accommodation and severe overcrowding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">▪</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">single people aged under 35 are moving out of borough.</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Few families have moved out of Hackney following </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the reduction in LHA, but have instead absorbed the rental shortfalls from their existing income. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">They now have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">little scope to cover further cuts and shortfalls. As the link between the market rent and the LHA rate has been broken, the disparity between t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he rents being charged and the support provided continues to grow significantly. The rents in Hackney have grown by over 6%, whereas the rise in the level of support has been pegged at 2.2%.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This also affects new households in Hackney, such as children who</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have left the parental home or families moving into the borough. They are finding that significantly less than 30% of the properties in the private sector are within their price range as a consequence of the LHA ceiling, even when they are in employment.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Homelessness is increasing in Hackney, in large part due to private landlords </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">no longer letting to families on housing support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or rents becoming increasingly unaffordable. Hackney has responsibility for 1696 households in temporary accommodation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an increase of 11.1% in 6 months.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The reform programme is inhibiting the ability of the Council to secure affordable accommodation for these households. The two Housing Association Leasing (HALS) providers working with Hackney have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">already issued their te</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nants notices to quit and are pulling out the sector due to the Benefit Cap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The reform of the LHA rate was intended to help control rent levels, but this has not been effective in Hackney</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nor in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a whole</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">factors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rising land/prop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erty values, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">resilient</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> economy and the lack of affordable stock are more important</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">drivers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This means that as rent levels in Hackney continue to rise, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disaggregating rental support from the market </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">means households do not have the confidence tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t they will be able continue to pay their rent over time, introducing an element of financial instability that inhibits long term planning. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a concern that many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">affected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> households </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are taking short term measures i.e. migrating from central </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to Hackney. Most will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be required to move again</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> within a few months.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The response by Hackney Council and partners</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hackney began working in earnest with residents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">around the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> benefit cap in November 2012. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Working</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Jobcentre staff</span><span style="font-family:Arial