"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As previously highlighted, market rents are particularly high in Hackney and look set to continue rising. The limited pool of accommodation that is affordable to low income househol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ds is rapidly depleting. The Council is looking at a number of initiatives to expand housing supply.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Building new homes is essential. The Council recognises the importance of the new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">affordable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">funding model </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> GLA Affordable Homes Programme 2011-2015</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in delivering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">new stock</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hackney has an excellent track record in delivery of new homes. The borough is a good place to invest and we are committed to working closely with partners to make sure that this remains the case in the future. That said, the intr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oduction of Affordable Rents in Hackney poses significant challenges.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.The Affordable Rent programme gives providers the flexibility to charge up to 80% of market rent, although the expectation is that rents will be set at around 65% of market value. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Howev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er, in practise this will still be unaffordable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to many low income households </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in real terms. 65% of the average market rent for a three bedroom property in Hackney exceeds £350.00 per week, which is more than the LHA rate set </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for the borough.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hackney is also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">investigating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the potential for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an in-house </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ocial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ettings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gency to recruit and encourage private landlords </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to provide properties to be let at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">affordable rent levels. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Private Sector Leasing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an important part of Hackney’s housing strate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gy. However, there has been a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">major</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> decline in the availability of such properties and an increasing reliance on significantly more expensive annexe accommodation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The development of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Social Lettings Agency equipped with a more attractive and secure offer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to landlords </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> assist in reversing this trend and provide greater support to tenants.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Social Lettings Agency will provide an umbrella for a range of possible private sector leasing arrangements. This includes the existing supplier framework and ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">w initiatives which will give the Council more control over the quality of accommodation and landlords and tenant support.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hackney’s priority is always to seek to support residents to remain within the locality. However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The acute shortage of suitable affo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rdable housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">throughout London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will require some households to move to other parts of the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As part of the work around potential out-of-London placements, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Council </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in place </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to help establish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> household</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">within</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> their new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">locality, for example help with placements in local schools and handovers to local health providers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is time consuming</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, particularly as many of these households have multiple needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Consequently, relocating the family is delayed pl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">acing an extended burden the Council.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How the government can help address these issues</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">costs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">significantly drives up the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cost of living in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This is recognised and reflected in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wage settlements, resulting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> average </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gross wage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">29% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">higher than the national median</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the benefit cap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, although </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">linked</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> median </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">earnings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> makes no such distinction. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a strong case for setting an amended cap for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on the same basis as the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cap, basing it on median earnings in the capital. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This would allow Hackney residents preparing for work to remain within the community and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">close to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local job markets. It will also protect those with limited job security or who take short term employment. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A similar affect would be achieved by removing financial support for housing from the cap calculation, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ap could then be adjusted to reflect a ceiling on support for maintenance while, in those areas where the benefit market is a driver for rent infla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion, the rental costs can be controlled by capping LHA rates.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In a similar vein, allowing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">additional protection from the cap for those households actively engaged in training/work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">preparation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, particularly where access to a scheme is not available or it i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s unreasonable to expect the applicant to accept a placement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, will provide the stability and the financial incentive to complete their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">course</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and improve the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ir chances of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sustainable employment. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hackney expect housing providers to take account of affordab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ility for local households in setting Affordable Rent levels in their proposals. To ensure affordability for future tenants in the borough, we expect rent levels to be significantly lower than local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">market rents. Registered providers should ensure that, in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> all cases, rents charged are within welfare benefit caps. Registered providers must also avoid setting rents in a way in which there could be a future risk of exceeding welfare caps.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Mayor for London, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as a part</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the London Plan, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> allow councils to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">set caps for affordable rents and rent targets in their planning frameworks. The government should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">make every effort to pursuade the Mayor to devolve these responsibilities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With rent inflation in Hackney at around 6%, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> little affo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rdable housing that is available will soon be unaffordable. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Re-establishing the link between support for housing costs and the local market rent levels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is essential to redress this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This could be funded by using the LHA Affordability fund to raise LHA rate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by either </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CPI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RPI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rates of inflation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Concerns remain that the removal of the option to pay housing support directly to social landlords within </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Universal Credit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will lead </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increased arrears, uncertainty over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cashflow </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undermine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">abil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ity to draw in investment for new build. The government should allow housing support payments to be paid direct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to social landlords</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Additionally, this option should be extended to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rivate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> landlords who engage with Private Sector Leasing schemes, pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oviding more financial security and encouraging them to remain within the sector.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><ol start="51" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Universal Credit (and the wider reform programme) has been designed to increase work incentives. Hackney supports this ambition. However, the ability for households to take advantage of these incentives </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is undermined if it does not also allow them to live </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">where the work, and the support network that enables them to work, is located. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>